============Sample ptraj analysis script================
trajin /users/sarahgra/mixmd/run_1/New4H_production.1.crd.bz2 1 1250 1

#Center and process image
center :1-161 mass origin
image origin familiar com :1-161

#Align trajectory to reference structure by minimizing RMSD
reference /users/sarahgra/mixmd/run_1/1P3.pdb
strip :Cl-,Na+
rms reference mass out 1P3_rmsd.txt :1-161@CA

#Write out grid count of probe occupancy
grid 1P3_10.0-20.0ns_1P3.xplor 200 0.5 200 0.5 200 0.5 :1P3 origin max 0.9
grid WAT_10.0-20.0ns_WAT.xplor 200 0.5 200 0.5 200 0.5 :WAT origin max 0.9

#Correct for systematic error induced by ptraj grid function
translate x -0.25 y -0.25 z -0.25

#Calculate Average Structure
average 1P3_avg_10.0-20.0ns.pdb :1-161 pdb append

===========================================================
You can normalize the output by running the enclosed python normalization script.  This outputs a normalized .xplor file which can also be visualized in pymol.  It also prints to the screen the pertinent stats on the distribution of occupancies (max, mean, std. deviation)

% python faster_normalize_xplor_density_cpptraj.py -x 1P3_10.0-20.0ns_1P3.xplor > stats_file

This can then be visualized in pymol (Chimera works well too and has a handy slider-GUI to contour the density)
1) Load the xplor files and average pdb
2) isomesh Pick_a_name, 1P3_10.0-20.0ns_1P3.xplor, 10 (The # corresponds to the occupancy of the probes)

If visualizing multiple maps of the same protein, you need to align the average structures and then move the maps to this new frame of reference
http://www.pymolwiki.org/index.php/Matrix_Copy

